  "beats": [
    {
      "beat_id": "B01",
      "act": "HOOK",
      "narration_text": "Namaste. Liam, in for Bear. Ask Claude why a sodium streetlight is yellow, and the answer begins with a symmetry that hydrogen has, but sodium breaks.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "remotion",
        "remotion": {
          "pattern": "ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "provenance": "proven-core/ClaudeComposerAsk",
          "version": "1",
          "props": {
            "command": "Why is sodium streetlight yellow, and what does hydrogen degeneracy have to do with it?",
            "topic": "QUANTUM MECHANICS — ATOMIC SPECTRA",
            "segment": "Why Sodium's Streetlight Is Yellow",
            "greeting": "Namaste, Liam",
            "runningText": "tracing the sodium D-line transition…",
            "output": [
              "Hydrogen's same-n levels are degenerate.",
              "Sodium's ionic core splits 3s from 3p."
            ],
            "folderLabel": "@NikBearBrown",
            "modelLabel": "Fable 5",
            "effortLabel": "High"
          },
          "rendered": {
            "out": "media/B01.mp4",
            "at": ""
          }
        }
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B01.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.98,
      "build": {
        "status": "VIDEO",
        "src": "media/B01.mp4",
        "filled_by": "media",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "act": "OBSERVE",
      "narration_text": "The familiar glow sits near five hundred eighty nine nanometers. It is actually a close pair of sodium D lines, unresolved by an ordinary glance.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.98,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "act": "BASELINE",
      "narration_text": "Start with ideal nonrelativistic hydrogen. For a Coulomb potential, every orbital with the same principal number n has the same energy, regardless of ell.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.79,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "act": "DEGENERACY",
      "narration_text": "So hydrogen's three s and three p levels line up. Different shapes, same energy. That accidental degeneracy comes from an extra symmetry of the one-over-r potential.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.15,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "act": "SODIUM",
      "narration_text": "Sodium is not a one-electron atom. Ten inner electrons form a closed neon-like core, leaving one valence electron outside.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.45,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "act": "SCREENING",
      "narration_text": "Far away, the core screens most of the nuclear charge. But an s orbital penetrates the core more strongly than a p orbital and feels a different effective potential.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 15,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.69,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "act": "SPLIT",
      "narration_text": "Turn on that non-Coulomb core interaction and the equal-energy levels split. The three s state drops well below the three p state.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 7.59,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "act": "EMISSION",
      "narration_text": "Excite sodium into three p. When it falls to three s, the energy gap leaves as a photon. Delta E equals h c over lambda.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.06,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "act": "NUMBER",
      "narration_text": "At five hundred eighty nine nanometers, that photon carries about two point one electron volts. The lamp converts a broken degeneracy into yellow light.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 13,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 9.32,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "act": "CAVEAT",
      "narration_text": "The real feature is a doublet near five eighty nine point zero and five eighty nine point six nanometers, mainly from spin-orbit splitting of three p. We omit that fine structure here.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 16,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.01,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "act": "SCOPE",
      "narration_text": "Screening alone is not the whole story. Penetration and the resulting quantum defects encode how each orbital samples the ionic core.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 8.28,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "act": "YOUR TURN",
      "narration_text": "Your turn. Use twelve forty electron-volt nanometers divided by five eighty nine nanometers. What transition energy do you get? About two point one electron volts.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 15,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.33,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B12.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B13",
      "act": "RECAP",
      "narration_text": "Hydrogen lines up states with equal n. Sodium's core breaks that ideal symmetry, splits three s from three p, and the returning electron announces the gap in yellow.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "manim"
      },
      "estimated_duration_s": 14,
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B13.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.43,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B13.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T18:12:03"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B14",
      "act": "OUTRO",
      "narration_text": "Why Sodium's Streetlight Is Yellow.",
